        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "When the DFT is computed for purely real input, the output is\nHermitian-symmetric, i.e. the negative frequency terms are just the complex\nconjugates of the corresponding positive-frequency terms, and the\nnegative-frequency terms are therefore redundant.  This function does not\ncompute the negative frequency terms, and the length of the transformed\naxis of the output is therefore "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "n//2 + 1"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "When "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "A = rfft(a)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " and fs is the sampling frequency, "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "A[0]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " contains\nthe zero-frequency term 0*fs, which is real due to Hermitian symmetry."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "If "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "n"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is even, "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "A[-1]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " contains the term representing both positive\nand negative Nyquist frequency (+fs/2 and -fs/2), and must also be purely\nreal. If "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "n"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is odd, there is no term at fs/2; "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "A[-1]"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " contains\nthe largest positive frequency (fs/2*(n-1)/n), and is complex in the\ngeneral case."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "If the input "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "a"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " contains an imaginary part, it is silently discarded."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "import whest as we"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.fft.fft([0, 1, 0, 0])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([ 1.+0.j,  0.-1.j, -1.+0.j,  0.+1.j]) # may vary"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "we.fft.rfft([0, 1, 0, 0])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([ 1.+0.j,  0.-1.j, -1.+0.j]) # may vary"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Notice how the final element of the "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "fft"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " output is the complex conjugate\nof the second element, for real input. For "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "rfft"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": ", this symmetry is\nexploited to compute only the non-negative frequency terms."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Examples"
